# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bristol-royal-hospital-for-children
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The trust provided services to a population of 1.6 million people in 2010.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Avon and Wiltshire Mental Health Partnership NHS Trust was established as the Bath Mental Health Care NHS Trust, on 1 November 1991.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Its name was changed on 1 April 1999 to the Avon and Western Wiltshire Mental Health Trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The Trust's name was again changed, on 1 April 2001, to Avon and Wiltshire Mental Health Partnership NHS Trust, following the merger of Avon and Western Wiltshire Mental Health Trust with services in Swindon and South Wiltshire.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In 2005, after an announced Healthcare Commission inspection, AWP's Barrow Hospital ranked bottom in the commission's table of hospital cleanliness.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The hospital, which was due to close the following year, closed three wards and reorganised housekeeping services.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In 2008, the Care Quality Commission (CQC) rated mental health services run by the trust as weak overall, along with ten other mental health trusts nationally.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] A 2012 CQC routine review found that the trust failed in four out of five inspection areas, and had insufficient experienced staff to meet needs.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In 2013, the CQC identified the trust as one of eight mental health trusts with units that had dangerous staffing levels.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In 2014, following an inspection, the CQC issued four warning notices to the trust requiring urgent action.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The trust was ordered to make urgent improvements to the safety of some of its services by the CQC in September 2014, after they found widespread inadequate staffing at inpatient units and a failure to investigate and learn from patient safety incidents.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Hayley Richards is retiring as chief executive in May 2019, and will be replaced by Dominic Hardisty, previously Chief Operating Officer and Deputy Chief Executive at Oxford Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Prior to the arrival of Hardisty, Simon Truelove, the trust's Director of Finance, will act as the interim CEO.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] A partnership of AWP, Second Step, Missing Link and seven voluntary sector organisations, called Bristol Mental Health, was awarded the contract.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Different organisations will be responsible for each of six areas of the service.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] Bristol Mental Health commenced operation in October 2014.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The trust in conjunction with other partners won a contract to provide children's community services in Bristol and South Gloucestershire in October 2015, after North Bristol NHS Trust announced it would give up the contract.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The service is provided by the Community Children's Health Partnership, which is a partnership between Sirona Care & Health, Bristol Community Health, Barnardo's and AWP.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In June 2024, the trust closed their only Learning Disability Ward, The Daisy, at Green Lane Hospital, Devizes.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] In 2024, the trust failed to secure the contract to deliver specialist learning disability, autism and ADHD community services in Bath and North East Somerset, Swindon and Wiltshire following an unsuccessful joint bid with the three local hospital trusts.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/avon-and-wiltshire-mental-health-partnership-nhs-trust] The contract awarded to HCRG Care Group Limited, who took over the running of BSW community services in April 2025.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Opened as a prison in 1779, many of its buildings and the co-located Glenside campus of the University of the West of England (UWE) are Grade II listed.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] From 1948 until 2005, the site was also a geriatric hospital, for many of those years being the major geriatric hospital in South West England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2009, 21 acres (8.5 ha) of the site, incorporating the oldest buildings, was sold to the UK Government's Homes and Communities Agency, for redevelopment as part of a wider regeneration project.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The site first came into use as a prison in 1779, during the American Revolutionary War, when it was developed to house Dutch and Spanish prisoners of war who had been landed at Bristol Docks.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After George III recognised the 13 United States of America as free and independent in 1783, the prisoners were sent home.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The site formally adopted the title 'Stapleton Prison', but was under utilised in civilian use, and was again expanded from 1793 after the commencement of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] A third prison building was completed in 1804, used most recently as nurses' accommodation.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After the Treaty of Paris of 1814, the prisoners were again repatriated.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Writing in London Labour and the London Poor, published in 1862, Henry Mayhew recounted a letter sent by the secretary of the Bristol Society for the Suppression of Vice in 1808: 'Sir, I took my horse and rode to Stapleton prison ...
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Inclosed are some of the drawings which I purchased in what they call their market ...
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] They wished to intrude on me a variety of devices in bone and wood of the most obscene kind ...
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] I purchased a few, but they are too bulky for a letter.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Used as a naval stores, and then a school for naval boys, after a cholera outbreak in 1834 led to overcrowding of Bristol's first workhouse at St Peter's Hospital, the Bristol Corporation of the Poor rented the old prison.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After purchasing the site in 1837, they began to make alterations, adding to the walls separating the different sections of the site.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 1861, they demolished many of the oldest prison buildings, and built the main structure of what later become Blackberry Hill Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] On the 1880 Ordnance Survey map it is shown as the **Bristol Union Workhouse**.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After the end of hostilities, these housing and post-assessment training activities continued.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After the Second World War, the National Health Service Act 1946 turned the informal retention activity into a full mental health facility, under the title Stapleton Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Records show that on take over by the NHS, the facility was caring for 837 patients: 350 under the Mental Treatment Act 1930; 152 mentally handicapped; 80 social misfits.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Even after takeover, the previous regime stayed in place, with patients assessed as capable enough working for their keep in the hospital's kitchens, bakery and for local farms.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] However, in 1948 it became Stapleton Hospital for Geriatric Illness.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Renamed under the NHS reforms of 1956, Manor Park Hospital retained its geriatric illness brief.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The hospital was staffed by eight consultancy teams, and much of its workhouse-related architecture was removed, reducing ward sizes, and replacing farming and work areas with gardens.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In the 1960s Manor Park Hospital was the major geriatric hospital in South West England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Patient turnover rose despite bed numbers gradually declining from about 650, to about 430 in 1977, due to length of stays decreasing.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] From January 1993, the hospital site merged with the adjacent Glenside Hospital, originally built as a lunatic asylum, to become the jointly named Blackberry Hill Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Patients of Glenside were assessed for capability, with many placed within the Care in the Community programme, while the residual were moved into new buildings constructed on the former Manor Park site for their long term care.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Geriatric services were initially run by the Frenchay Healthcare Trust, which took in patients from a wide area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 1997, the newly created North Bristol NHS Trust (NBT), merging the operations of Frenchay Hospital and Southmead Hospital, took over the running of these services and focused on patients from the trust catchment area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In June 2005, NBT closed inpatient services at Blackberry Hill Hospital, transferring most services to Frenchay Hospital and Southmead Hospital, with the objective of improving services while reducing costs.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Stroke services, orthopedic rehabilitation services, dementia services and intermediate care services were moved from Blackberry Hill Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] A small respite care service was transferred to Thornbury Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Associated with the move, an inpatient service for elderly mental health patients run by Avon and Wiltshire Mental Health Partnership Trust (AWP) at Blackberry Hill was enlarged in size.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] Some geriatric outpatient services remained at the site, including the Memory Service.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] However, in 2006 AWP took over the running of the Memory Service, following the national model of Mental Health Trusts running this service.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] A charity for research into Alzheimer's disease, BRACE, and the Regional Quality Control Laboratories continued to use the site under a lease from NBT until July 2010.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2005, AWP created, two new secured facilities at Blackberry Hill.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The first was a refurbishment of the secure in-patient care facility to create the Wickham Unit (or Wickham Low Secure Service).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The second in new buildings to the rear of the site provided a medium secure facility, known as Fromeside (or Fromeside Medium Secure Unit).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 1996, the Avon and Gloucestershire College of Health (along with the Bath and Swindon College of Health Studies) became part of the University of the West of England (UWE), and the Glenside site became the UWE Faculty of Health and Social Care.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2013, AWP was given a formal warning by the Care Quality Commission over low staffing levels at its medium-secure unit on the site.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2005, North Bristol NHS Trust transferred most of their remaining services to Frenchay and Southmead Hospitals.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2007, they declared the Blackberry Hill site surplus to requirements, while AWP moved some of its older people services to Callington Road and Southmead hospitals.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] After transferring their 10% interest in the site to NBT, AWP adult mental health services were moved to the most modern buildings at the rear of the hospital site.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2009, the residual 21 acres (8.5 ha) Blackberry Hill site was sold to the UK Government's Homes and Communities Agency to be redeveloped as part of a wider regeneration project.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] The buildings which are mainly Grade II listed will be converted into a mixed-use development of flats, houses, shops and small business premises.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/blackberry-hill-hospital] In 2017, it was announced that 346 houses would be built on the site.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] The Archives moved from the City Hall to newly converted premises in the former B Bond Warehouse in 1992.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] The office is formally recognised by the Lord Chancellor for holding public records, and it acts as a diocesan record office for the Diocese of Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Major deposited collections include those of J.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Fry & Sons, chocolate manufacturers, 1693–1966, and Imperial Brands (formerly W.D. & H.O.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Wills, tobacco manufacturers), late 18th century – 20th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] However, for many years one of its best-known holdings was a single volume of judicial case papers bound in the actual skin of the 19th-century executed murderer John Horwood.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Bristol Archives is part of Bristol Museums, along with Bristol Museum & Art Gallery, M Shed, Georgian House, Red Lodge, Blaise Castle, and Kings Weston Roman Villa.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] The core opening hours are Tuesday - Friday, 9:30 am-4 pm.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] In addition, on the first two Saturdays of the month, Bristol Archives is open 10 am-4 pm.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Bristol Archives holds material related to the port of Bristol from the 13th century onwards.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-archives] Further records are held by the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-eye-hospital] The hospital was founded in 1808 by Dr William Henry Goldwyer as "The Institution for the Cure of Disease of the Eye Amongst the Poor" in Lower Maudlin Street.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-eye-hospital] In 1839, and again in 1898, it expanded into adjoining buildings.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-eye-hospital] In 1935 a new building was completed, which was in turn replaced in 1982 creating the present hospital which opened in 1986.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-eye-hospital] A refurbishment and expansion took place between 2010 and 2011.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The county is almost entirely urbanised and had an estimated population of 494,399 in 2024, making Bristol the most populous city in the region.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] For local government purposes the county is a unitary authority area governed by Bristol City Council.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The council is a member of the West of England Combined Authority, which allows it to collaborate with South Gloucestershire Council and Bath and North East Somerset Council.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Iron Age hillforts and Roman villas were built near the confluence of the rivers Frome and Avon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol received a royal charter in 1155, but was historically divided between Gloucestershire and Somerset until it became a county corporate in 1373.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] From the 13th to the 18th centuries, Bristol was among the top three English cities, after London, in tax receipts.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A major port, Bristol was a starting place for early voyages of exploration to the New World.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] At the height of the Bristol slave trade, from 1700 to 1807, more than 2,000 slave ships carried an estimated 500,000 people from Africa to slavery in the Americas.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Port of Bristol has since moved from Bristol Harbour in the city centre to the Severn Estuary at Avonmouth and Royal Portbury Dock.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city's modern economy is built on the creative media, electronics, and aerospace industries; the city-centre docks have been redeveloped as cultural and heritage centres.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] There are a variety of artistic and sporting organisations and venues, including the Royal West of England Academy, the Arnolfini, Ashton Gate and the Memorial Ground.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city has two universities: the University of Bristol and the University of the West of England (UWE Bristol).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It is connected to the world by Bristol Airport; to the rest of Great Britain via Bristol Temple Meads and Bristol Parkway mainline rail stations; and by road by both the south-west to West Midlands M5 and the London to South Wales M4 (which connect to the city centre by the Portway and M32).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The name derives from the Old English *Brycgstow*, meaning "assembly place by the bridge" or simply "site of the bridge", presumably in reference to a crossing over the Avon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The final 'L' is an unetymological addition that first appears in the 12th century, which may be due to the unique "Terminal L" found in the Bristol dialect.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] An older form of the name survives as the surname Bristow, which is derived from the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Archaeological finds, including flint tools believed to be between 300,000 and 126,000 years old made with the Levallois technique, indicate the presence of Neanderthals in the Shirehampton and St Annes areas of Bristol during the Middle Palaeolithic.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Iron Age hill forts near the city are at Leigh Woods and Clifton Down, on the side of the Avon Gorge, and on Kings Weston Hill near Henbury.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A Roman port, *Portus Abonae* (Avonport) – abbreviated to *Abona* in the Antonine Itinerary, existed at what is now Sea Mills (connected to Bath and Gloucester by Roman roads); another settlement was at the present-day Inns Court.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Isolated Roman villas and small forts and settlements were also scattered throughout the area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was founded by 1000; by about 1020, it was a trading centre with a mint producing silver pennies bearing its name.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] By 1067, Brycgstow was a well-fortified *burh*, and that year the townsmen beat back a raiding party from Ireland led by three of Harold Godwinson's sons.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Under Norman rule, the town had one of the strongest castles in southern England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was the place of exile for Diarmait Mac Murchada, the Irish king of Leinster, after being overthrown.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Bristol merchants subsequently played a prominent role in funding Richard Strongbow de Clare and the Norman invasion of Ireland.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The port developed in the 11th century around the confluence of the Rivers Frome and Avon, adjacent to Bristol Bridge just outside the town walls.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] By the 12th century, there was an important Jewish community in Bristol which survived through to the late 13th century when all Jews were expelled from England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The stone bridge built in 1247 was replaced by the current bridge during the 1760s.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The town incorporated neighbouring suburbs and became a county in 1373, the first town in England to be given this status.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During this period, Bristol became a shipbuilding and manufacturing centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] By the 14th century, Bristol, York and Norwich were England's largest medieval towns after London.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] One-third to one-half of the population died in the Black Death of 1348–49, which checked population growth, and its population remained between 10,000 and 12,000 for most of the 15th and 16th centuries.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the 15th century, Bristol was the second most important port in the country, trading with Ireland, Iceland and Gascony.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It was the starting point for many voyages, including Robert Sturmy's (1457–58) unsuccessful attempt to break the Italian monopoly of Eastern Mediterranean trade.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] New exploration voyages were launched by Venetian John Cabot, who in 1497 made landfall in North America.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A 1499 voyage, led by merchant William Weston of Bristol, was the first expedition commanded by an Englishman to North America.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the first decade of the 16th century, Bristol's merchants undertook a series of exploration voyages to North America and even founded a commercial organisation, 'The Company Adventurers to the New Found Land', to assist their endeavours.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] However, they seem to have lost interest in North America after 1509, having incurred great expenses and made little profit.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the 16th century, Bristol merchants concentrated on developing trade with Spain and its American colonies.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] This included the smuggling of prohibited goods, such as food and guns, to Iberia during the Anglo-Spanish War (1585–1604).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol's illicit trade grew enormously after 1558, becoming integral to its economy.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The original Diocese of Bristol was founded in 1542, when the former Abbey of St.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Augustine (founded by Robert Fitzharding four hundred years earlier) became Bristol Cathedral.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol also gained city status that year.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In the 1640s, during the English Civil War, the city was occupied by Royalists, who built the Royal Fort House on the site of an earlier Parliamentarian stronghold.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Fishermen from Bristol, who had fished the Grand Banks of Newfoundland since the 16th century, began settling Newfoundland permanently in larger numbers during the 17th century, establishing colonies at Bristol's Hope and Cuper's Cove.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Growth of the city and trade came with the rise of England's American colonies in the 17th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol's location on the west side of Great Britain gave its ships an advantage in sailing to and from the New World, and the city's merchants made the most of it, with the city becoming one of the two leading outports in all of England by the middle of the 18th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was the slave capital of England: In 1755, it had the largest number of slave traders in the country with 237, as against London's 147.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It was a major supplier of slaves to South Carolina before 1750.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 18th century saw an expansion of Bristol's population (45,000 in 1750) and its role in the Atlantic trade in Africans taken for slavery to the Americas.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol and later Liverpool became centres of the Triangular Trade.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Manufactured goods were shipped to West Africa and exchanged for Africans; the enslaved captives were transported across the Atlantic to the Americas in the Middle Passage under brutal conditions.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Plantation goods such as sugar, tobacco, rum, rice, cotton and a few slaves (sold to the aristocracy as house servants) returned across the Atlantic to England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Some household slaves were baptised in the hope this would lead them to be freed.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Somersett Case of 1772 clarified that slavery was illegal in England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] At the height of the Bristol slave trade from 1700 to 1807, more than 2,000 slave ships carried a conservatively estimated 500,000 people from Africa to slavery in the Americas.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 1739, John Wesley founded the first Methodist chapel, the New Room, in Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Wesley, along with his brother Charles Wesley and George Whitefield, preached to large congregations in Bristol and the neighbouring village of Kingswood, often in the open air.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Wesley published a pamphlet on slavery, titled *Thoughts Upon Slavery,* in 1774 and the Society of Friends began lobbying against slavery in Bristol in 1783.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city's scions remained nonetheless strongly anti-abolitionist.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Thomas Clarkson came to Bristol to study the slave trade and gained access to the Society of Merchant Venturers records.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] One of his contacts was the owner of the Seven Stars public house, who boarded sailors Clarkson sought to meet.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Through these sailors he was able to observe how slaver captains and first mates "plied and stupefied seamen with drink" to sign them up.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Other informants included ship surgeons and seamen seeking redress.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] When William Wilberforce began his parliamentary abolition campaign on 12 May 1788, he recalled the history of the Irish slave trade from Bristol, which he provocatively claimed continued into the reign of Henry VII.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Hannah More, originally from Bristol, and a good friend of both Wilberforce and Clarkson, published "Slavery, A Poem" in 1788, just as Wilberforce began his parliamentary campaign.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] His major speech on 2 April 1792 likewise described the Bristol slave trade specifically, and led to the arrest, trial and subsequent acquittal of a local slaver captain named Kimber.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city was associated with Victorian engineer Isambard Kingdom Brunel, who designed the Great Western Railway between Bristol and London Paddington, two pioneering Bristol-built oceangoing steamships (SS *Great Britain* and SS *Great Western*), and the Clifton Suspension Bridge.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The new railway replaced the Kennet and Avon Canal, which had fully opened in 1810, as the main route for the transport of goods between Bristol and London.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Competition from Liverpool (beginning around 1760), disruptions of maritime commerce due to war with France (1793) and the abolition of the slave trade (1807) contributed to Bristol's failure to keep pace with the newer manufacturing centres of Northern England and the West Midlands.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The tidal Avon Gorge, which had secured the port during the Middle Ages, had become a liability.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] An 1804–09 plan to improve the city's port with a floating harbour designed by William Jessop was a costly error, requiring high harbour fees.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the 19th century, Samuel Plimsoll, known as "the sailor's friend", campaigned to make the seas safer; shocked by overloaded vessels, he successfully fought for a compulsory load line on ships.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] By 1867, ships were getting larger and the meanders in the river Avon prevented boats over 300 ft (90 m) from reaching the harbour, resulting in falling trade.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The port facilities were migrating downstream to Avonmouth and new industrial complexes were founded there.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Some of the traditional industries including copper and brass manufacture went into decline, but the import and processing of tobacco flourished with the expansion of the W.D. & H.O.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Supported by new industry and growing commerce, Bristol's population (66,000 in 1801), quintupled during the 19th century, resulting in the creation of new suburbs such as Clifton and Cotham.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] These provide architectural examples from the Georgian to the Regency style, with many fine terraces and villas facing the road, and at right angles to it.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In the early 19th century, the romantic medieval gothic style appeared, partially as a reaction against the symmetry of Palladianism, and can be seen in buildings such as the Bristol City Museum and Art Gallery, the Royal West of England Academy, and The Victoria Rooms.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Riots broke out in 1793 and 1831; the first over the renewal of tolls on Bristol Bridge, and the second against the rejection of the second Reform Bill by the House of Lords.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The population by 1841 had reached 140,158.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Diocese of Bristol had undergone several boundary changes by 1897 when it was "reconstituted" into the configuration which has lasted into the 21st century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] From a population of about 330,000 in 1901, Bristol grew steadily during the 20th century, peaking at 428,089 in 1971.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Its Avonmouth docklands were enlarged during the early 1900s by the Royal Edward Dock.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Another new dock, the Royal Portbury Dock, opened across the river from Avonmouth during the 1970s.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] As air travel grew in the first half of the century, aircraft manufacturers built factories.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The unsuccessful Bristol International Exhibition was held on Ashton Meadows in the Bower Ashton area in 1914.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] After the premature closure of the exhibition the site was used, until 1919, as barracks for the Gloucestershire Regiment during World War I.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was heavily damaged by Luftwaffe raids during World War II; about 1,300 people living or working in the city were killed, and nearly 100,000 buildings were damaged, at least 3,000 beyond repair.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The original central shopping area, near the bridge and castle, is now a park containing two bombed churches and fragments of the castle.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A third bomb-damaged church nearby, St Nicholas, was restored and, after a period as a museum, has now re-opened as a church.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It houses a 1756 William Hogarth triptych painted for the high altar of St Mary Redcliffe.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The rebuilding of Bristol city centre was characterised by 1960s and 1970s skyscrapers, mid-century modern architecture and road building.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Beginning in the 1980s some main roads were closed, the Georgian-era Queen Square and Portland Square were restored, the Broadmead shopping area regenerated, and one of the city centre's tallest mid-century towers was demolished.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was bombed twice by the IRA, in 1974 and again in 1978.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 20th-century relocation of the docks to Avonmouth Docks and Royal Portbury Dock, 7 mi (11 km) downstream from the city centre, has allowed the redevelopment of the old dock area (the Floating Harbour).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Although the docks' existence was once in jeopardy (since the area was seen as a derelict industrial site), the inaugural 1996 International Festival of the Sea held in and around the docks affirmed the area as a leisure asset of the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] On 7 June 2020 a Statue of Edward Colston was pulled down from its city centre plinth by protestors and pushed into the harbour.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The statue was recovered on 11 June and has become a museum exhibit.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The action followed more than a decade of debate over the statue and the wording of its plaque, which commemorated Colston's philanthropic work in the city while making no reference to his role in the Royal African Company and the Bristol Slave Trade.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol City council consists of 70 councillors representing 34 wards, with between one and three per ward serving four-year terms.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] As of May 2024, no party has an overall controlling majority, but the Green Party are the largest group on the council.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Between 2012 and 2024, the council was led by a directly elected mayor, the Mayor of Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The post was abolished following a 2022 referendum, in which voters chose to replace it with a council committee system.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The lord mayor of Bristol is a figurehead elected each May by the city council.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The lord mayor (2026) is Henry Michallat.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In the House of Commons, Bristol is represented by five constituencies, East, North East, North West, South, and Central.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city has a tradition of political activism.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Edmund Burke, MP for the Bristol constituency for six years beginning in 1774, insisted that he was a Member of Parliament first and a representative of his constituents' interests second.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Women's-rights advocate Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence (1867–1954) was born in Bristol, and the left-winger Tony Benn served as MP for Bristol South East from 1950 to 1960 and again from 1963 to 1983.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 1963 the Bristol Bus Boycott, following the Bristol Omnibus Company's refusal to hire black drivers and conductors, drove the passage of the UK's 1965 Race Relations Act.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 1980 St Pauls riot protested against racism and police harassment and showed mounting dissatisfaction with the socioeconomic circumstances of the city's Afro-Caribbean residents.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Local support of fair trade was recognised in 2005, when Bristol became a fairtrade zone.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is both a city and a county, since King Edward III granted it a county charter in 1373.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The county was expanded in 1835 to include suburbs such as Clifton, and it was named a county borough in 1889 when that designation was introduced.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] On 1 April 1974, Bristol became a local government district of the administrative county of Avon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] On 1 April 1996, Avon was abolished and Bristol became a unitary authority.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The former Avon area, called Greater Bristol by the Government Office of the South West (now abolished) and others, refers to the city and the three neighbouring local authorities‍—‌Bath and North East Somerset, North Somerset and South Gloucestershire previously in Avon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The North Fringe of Bristol, a developed area between the Bristol city boundary and the M4, M5 and M32 motorways (now in South Gloucestershire) was so named as part of a 1987 plan prepared by the Northavon District Council of Avon county.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The West of England Combined Authority was created on 9 February 2017.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Covering Bristol and the rest of the old Avon county with the exception of North Somerset, the new combined authority has responsibility for regional planning, roads, and local transport, and to a lesser extent, education and business investment.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The authority is led by the Mayor of the West of England, Helen Godwin.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol's boundaries can be defined in several ways, including those of the city itself, the developed area, or Greater Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city council boundary is the narrowest definition of the city itself.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] However, it unusually includes a large, roughly rectangular section of the western Severn Estuary ending at (but not including) the islands of Flat Holm (in Cardiff, Wales) and Steep Holm.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] This "seaward extension" can be traced back to the original boundary of the County of Bristol laid out in the charter granted to the city by Edward III in 1373.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol lies within a limestone area running from the Mendip Hills in the south to the Cotswolds in the northeast.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The rivers Avon and Frome cut through the limestone to the underlying clay, creating Bristol's characteristically hilly landscape.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Avon flows from Bath in the east, through flood plains and areas which were marshes before the city's growth.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] To the west, the Avon cuts through the limestone to form the Avon Gorge, formed largely by glacial meltwater after the last ice age.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The gorge, which helped protect Bristol Harbour, has been quarried for stone to build the city, and its surrounding land has been protected from development as The Downs and Leigh Woods.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Avon estuary and the gorge form the county boundary with North Somerset, and the river flows into the Severn Estuary at Avonmouth.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A smaller gorge, cut by the Hazel Brook which flows into the River Trym, crosses the Blaise Castle estate in northern Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is sometimes described, by its inhabitants, as being built on seven hills, like Rome.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] From 18th-century guidebooks, these seven hills were known as simply Bristol (the Old Town), Castle Hill, College Green, Kingsdown, St Michael's Hill, Brandon Hill and Redcliffe Hill.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Other local hills include Red Lion Hill, Barton Hill, Lawrence Hill, Black Boy Hill, Constitution Hill, Staple Hill, Windmill Hill, Malborough Hill, Nine Tree Hill, Talbot, Brook Hill and Granby Hill.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is 106 mi (171 km) west of London, 77 mi (124 km) south-southwest of Birmingham and 26 mi (42 km) east of the Welsh capital Cardiff.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Areas adjoining the city fall within a loosely defined area known as Greater Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bath is located 11 mi (18 km) southeast of the city centre, Weston-super-Mare is 18 mi (29 km) to the southwest and the Welsh city of Newport is 19 mi (31 km) to the north west.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The climate is oceanic (Köppen: *Cfb)*, milder than most places in England and United Kingdom.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Located in southern England, Bristol is one of the warmest cities in the UK with a mean annual temperature of approximately 11 °C (52 °F).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It is among the sunniest, with more than 1,600 hours of sunshine per year.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Although the city is partially sheltered by the Mendip Hills, it is exposed to the Severn Estuary and the Bristol Channel.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Rain is fairly evenly distributed throughout the year, with autumn and winter the wetter seasons.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Atlantic Ocean influences Bristol's weather, keeping its average temperature above freezing throughout the year, but winter frosts are frequent and snow occasionally falls from early November to late April.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Summers are warm and drier, with variable sunshine, rain and clouds, and spring weather is unsettled.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The weather stations nearest Bristol for which long-term climate data are available are Long Ashton (about 5 mi (8 km) south west of the city centre) and Bristol Weather Station, in the city centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Data collection at these locations ended in 2002 and 2001, respectively, and following the closure of Filton Airfield, Almondsbury is the nearest weather station to the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Monthly high temperatures since 2002 at Filton exceeding those recorded at Long Ashton include 25.7 °C (78.3 °F) in April 2003, 34.5 °C (94.1 °F) in July 2006 and 26.8 °C (80.2 °F) in October 2011.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The lowest recent temperature at Filton was −10.1 °C (13.8 °F) in December 2010.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Although large cities in general experience an urban heat island effect, with warmer temperatures than their surrounding rural areas, this phenomenon is minimal in Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] From 1958 to 2002, extremes were recorded at Long Ashton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Since 2002, extremes were recorded at Filton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol was ranked as Britain's most sustainable city (based on its environmental performance, quality of life, future-proofing and approaches to climate change, recycling and biodiversity), topping environmental charity Forum for the Future's 2008 Sustainable Cities Index.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Local initiatives include Sustrans (creators of the National Cycle Network, founded as Cyclebag in 1977) and Resourcesaver, a non-profit business established in 1988 by Avon Friends of the Earth.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city regularly features in the annual *Sunday Times* lists of best places in Britain in which to live, topping the list of cities in 2014 and 2017.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city received the 2015 European Green Capital Award, becoming the first UK city to receive this award.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2019 Bristol City Council voted in favour of banning all privately owned diesel cars from the city centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Since then, the plans have been revised in favour of a clean air zone whereby older and more polluting vehicles will be charged to drive through the city centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Clean Air Zone came into effect in November 2022.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city has a green belt mainly along its southern fringes, taking in small areas within the Ashton Court Estate, South Bristol crematorium and cemetery, High Ridge common and Whitchurch, with a further area around Frenchay Farm.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The belt extends outside the city boundaries into surrounding counties and districts, for several miles in places, to afford protection from urban sprawl to surrounding villages and towns.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In the 2021 census, the religious composition of the city of Bristol comprised: 32.2% Christian, 51.4% no religion, 6.7% Muslim, 0.8% Hindu, 0.6% Buddhist, 0.5% Sikh, 0.3% Jewish, 0.8% Other religion, and 6.9% not stated.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Among the notable Christian churches are the Anglican Bristol Cathedral and St Mary Redcliffe and the Roman Catholic Clifton Cathedral.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Nonconformist chapels include Buckingham Baptist Chapel and John Wesley's New Room in Broadmead.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] After St James' Presbyterian Church was bombed on 24 November 1940, it was never again used as a church; although its bell tower remains, its nave was converted into offices.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city has eleven mosques, several Buddhist meditation centres, a Hindu temple, Reform and Orthodox-Jewish synagogues and four Sikh temples.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The population of Bristol's contiguous urban area was put at 551,066 by the ONS based on Census 2001 data.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2006 the ONS estimated Bristol's urban-area population at 587,400, making it England's sixth-most populous city and tenth-most populous urban area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] At 3,599/km2 (9,321/sq mi) it has the seventh-highest population density of any English district.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] According to data from 2019, the urban area has the 11th-largest population in the UK, with a population of 670,000.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2007 the European Spatial Planning Observation Network (ESPON) defined Bristol's functional urban area as including Weston-super-Mare, Bath and Clevedon with a total population of 1.04 million, the twelfth largest of the UK.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol has a long history of trade, originally exporting wool cloth and importing fish, wine, grain and dairy products; later imports were tobacco, tropical fruits and plantation goods.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Major imports are motor vehicles, grain, timber, produce and petroleum products.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city's economy also relies on the aerospace, defence, media, information technology, financial services and tourism industries.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Ministry of Defence (MoD)'s Procurement Executive, later known as the Defence Procurement Agency and Defence Equipment and Support, moved to its headquarters to Abbey Wood, Filton, in 1995.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] This organisation, with a staff of 12,000 to 13,000, procures and supports MoD equipment.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] One of the UK's most popular tourist destinations, Bristol was selected in 2009 as one of the world's top-ten cities by international travel publishers Dorling Kindersley in their *Eyewitness* guides for young adults.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is one of the eight-largest regional English cities that make up the Core Cities Group, and is ranked as a Gamma level global city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, the fourth-highest-ranked English city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2017 Bristol's gross domestic product was £88.448 billion.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Its per capita GDP was £46,000 ($65,106, €57,794), which was some 65% above the national average, the third-highest of any English city (after London and Nottingham) and the sixth-highest of any city in the United Kingdom (behind London, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Belfast and Nottingham).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] According to the 2011 census, Bristol's unemployment rate (claiming Jobseeker's Allowance) was three per cent, compared with two per cent for South West England and the national average of four per cent.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Although Bristol's economy no longer relies upon its port, which was moved to docks at Avonmouth during the 1870s and to the Royal Portbury Dock in 1977 as ship size increased, it is the largest importer of cars to the UK.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Until 1991, the port was publicly owned; it is leased, with £330 million invested and its annual tonnage increasing from 3.9 million long tons (4 million tonnes) to 11.8 million (12 million).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Tobacco importing and cigarette manufacturing have ceased, but the importation of wine and spirits continues.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The financial services sector employs 59,000 in the city, and 50 micro-electronics and silicon design companies employ about 5,000.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 1983, Hewlett-Packard opened its national research laboratory in Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2014 the city was ranked seventh in the "top 10 UK destinations" by TripAdvisor.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the 20th century, Bristol's manufacturing activities expanded to include aircraft production at Filton by the Bristol Aeroplane Company and aircraft-engine manufacturing by Bristol Aero Engines (later Rolls-Royce) at Patchway.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol Aeroplane was known for their World War I Bristol Fighter and World War II Blenheim and Beaufighter planes.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the 1950s, they were a major English manufacturer of civilian aircraft, known for the Freighter, Britannia and Brabazon.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The company diversified into automobile manufacturing during the 1940s, producing hand-built luxury Bristol Cars at their factory in Filton, and the Bristol Cars company was spun off in 1960.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city also gave its name to Bristol buses, which were manufactured in the city from 1908 to 1983: by Bristol Tramways until 1955, and from 1955 to 1983 by Bristol Commercial Vehicles.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Filton played a key role in the Anglo-French Concorde supersonic airliner project during the 1960s.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The British Concorde prototype made its maiden flight from Filton to RAF Fairford on 9 April 1969, five weeks after the French test flight.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2003 British Airways and Air France decided to discontinue Concorde flights, retiring the aircraft to locations (primarily museums) worldwide.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] On 26 November 2003 Concorde 216 made the final Concorde flight, returning to Bristol Filton Airport as the centrepiece of a proposed air museum which is planned to include the existing Bristol Aero collection (including a Bristol Britannia).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The aerospace industry remains a major sector of the local economy.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Major aerospace companies in Bristol include BAE Systems, a merger of Marconi Electronic Systems and BAe (the latter a merger of BAC, Hawker Siddeley and Scottish Aviation).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Airbus and Rolls-Royce are also based at Filton, and aerospace engineering is an area of research at the University of the West of England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Another aviation company in the city is Cameron Balloons, who manufacture hot air balloons; each August the city hosts the Bristol International Balloon Fiesta, one of Europe's largest hot-air balloon festivals.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2005, Bristol was named by the UK government one of England's six science cities.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A £500 million shopping centre, Cabot Circus, opened in 2008 amidst predictions by developers and politicians that the city would become one of England's top ten retail destinations.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Bristol Temple Quarter Enterprise Zone, focused on creative, high-tech and low-carbon industries around Bristol Temple Meads railway station, was announced in 2011 and launched the following year.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 70 ha (170-acre) Urban Enterprise Zone has streamlined planning procedures and reduced business rates.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Rates generated by the zone are channelled to five other designated enterprise areas in the region: Avonmouth, Bath, Bristol and Bath Science Park in Emersons Green, Filton, and Weston-super-Mare.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is the only big city whose wealth per capita is higher than that of Britain as a whole.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The wider region has one of the biggest aerospace hubs in the UK, centred on Airbus, Rolls-Royce and GKN at Filton airfield.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Between 2012 and 2020, the city had the largest circulating community currency in the UK, the Bristol Pound, which was pegged to the pound sterling before it ceased operation.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Some of the modern venues and modern digital production companies have merged with legacy production companies based in old buildings around the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2008 the city was a finalist for the 2008 European Capital of Culture, although the title was awarded to Liverpool.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city was designated "City of Film" by UNESCO in 2017 and has been a member of the Creative Cities Network since then.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Bristol Old Vic, founded in 1946 as an offshoot of The Old Vic in London, occupies the 1766 Theatre Royal (607 seats) on King Street and the Weston Studio in the adjacent Coopers' Hall (built in 1743), with a 2018 bar and foyer area.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Theatre Royal, a grade I listed building, is the oldest continuously operating theatre in England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Bristol Old Vic Theatre School (which originated in King Street) is a separate company, and the Bristol Hippodrome is a 1,951-seat theatre for national touring productions.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Other smaller theatres include the Tobacco Factory, QEH, the Redgrave Theatre at Clifton College, The Wardrobe Theatre, Bristol Improv Theatre, and the Alma Theatre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol's theatre scene features several companies as well as the Old Vic, including Show of Strength, Shakespeare at the Tobacco Factory and Travelling Light.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Theatre Bristol is a partnership between the city council, Arts Council England and local residents to develop the city's theatre industry.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Several organisations support Bristol theatre; the Residence (an artist-led community) provides office, social and rehearsal space for theatre and performance companies, and Equity has a branch in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city has many venues for live music, its largest being the 2,000-seat Bristol Beacon, previously Colston Hall, named after Edward Colston.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Others include the Bristol Academy, The Fleece, The Croft, the Exchange, Fiddlers, the Victoria Rooms, Rough Trade, Trinity Centre, St George's Bristol and several pubs, from the jazz-oriented The Old Duke to rock at the Fleece and indie bands at the Louisiana.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In 2010 PRS for Music called Bristol the UK's most musical city, based on the number of its members born there relative to the city's population.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Since the late 1970s, Bristol has been home to bands combining punk, funk, dub and political consciousness.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] With trip hop and Bristol Sound artists such as Tricky, Portishead and Massive Attack, the list of bands from Bristol is extensive.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city is a stronghold of drum and bass, with artists such as Roni Size's Mercury Prize-winning Reprazent, as DJ Krust, More Rockers and TC.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Musicians were at the centre of the broader Bristol urban-culture scene which received international media attention during the 1990s.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Downs Festival is also a yearly occurrence where both local and well-known bands play.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Since its inception in 2016, it has become a major event in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Bristol Museum and Art Gallery houses a collection encompassing natural history, archaeology, local glassware, Chinese ceramics and art.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The M Shed museum opened in 2011 on the site of the former Bristol Industrial Museum.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Both are operated by Bristol Culture and Creative Industries, which also runs three historic houses‍—‌the Tudor Red Lodge, the Georgian House and Blaise Castle House; and Bristol Archives.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 18th- and 19th-century portrait painter Thomas Lawrence, 19th-century architect Francis Greenway (designer of many of Sydney's first buildings) were born in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The graffiti artist Banksy is believed to be from Bristol, and many of his works are on display in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The Watershed Media Centre and Arnolfini gallery (both in dockside warehouses) exhibit contemporary art, photography and cinema, and the city's oldest gallery is at the Royal West of England Academy in Clifton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The nomadic Antlers Gallery opened in 2010, moving into empty spaces on Park Street, on Whiteladies Road and in the Purifier House on Bristol's Harbourside.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Stop-motion animation films and commercials (produced by Aardman Animations) are made in Bristol, such as *Wallace and Gromit* and *Chicken Run*, while Aardman has also branched out into computer-animation, such as *Arthur Christmas*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Robert Newton, Bobby Driscoll and other cast members of the 1950 Walt Disney film *Treasure Island* (some scenes were filmed along the harbourside) visited the city along with Disney himself.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is home to the regional headquarters of BBC West and the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Locations in and around Bristol have featured in the BBC's natural-history programmes, including *Animal Magic* (filmed at Bristol Zoo).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol is the birthplace of 18th-century poets Robert Southey and Thomas Chatterton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Southey (born on Wine Street in 1774) and his friend, Samuel Taylor Coleridge, married the Fricker sisters from the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] William Wordsworth spent time in Bristol, where Joseph Cottle published *Lyrical Ballads* in 1798.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Actor Cary Grant was born in Bristol, and comedians from the city include Justin Lee Collins, Lee Evans, Russell Howard and writer-comedian Stephen Merchant.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The author John Betjeman wrote a poem called "Bristol".
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol has 51 Grade I, 500 Grade II* and over 3,800 Grade II listed buildings in a variety of architectural styles, from medieval to modern.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During the mid-19th century, Bristol Byzantine, a style unique to the city, was developed, and several examples have survived.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Buildings from most architectural periods of the United Kingdom can be seen in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Surviving elements of the fortifications and castle date to the medieval period, and the Church of St James dates back to the 12th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The oldest Grade I listed buildings in Bristol are religious.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] St James' Priory was founded in 1129 as a Benedictine priory by Earl Robert of Gloucester, the illegitimate son of Henry I.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The second-oldest is Bristol Cathedral and its associated Great Gatehouse.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Founded in 1140 as an Augustinian monastery, the church became the seat of the bishop and cathedral of the new Diocese of Bristol in 1542.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Most of the medieval stonework, particularly the Elder Lady Chapel, is made from limestone taken from quarries around Dundry and Felton, with Bath stone being used in other areas.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Amongst the other churches included in the list is the 12th-century St Mary Redcliffe which is the second tallest building in Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Secular buildings include The Red Lodge, built in 1580 for John Yonge as a lodge for a larger house that once stood on the site of the present Bristol Beacon, previously known as Colston Hall.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It was added to in Georgian times and restored in the early 20th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] St Bartholomew's Hospital is a 12th-century town house which was incorporated into a monastery hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] It was founded in 1240 by Sir John la Warr, 2nd Baron De La Warr (c.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] 1277–1347), and became Bristol Grammar School from 1532 to 1767, and then Queen Elizabeth's Hospital 1767–1847.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The round piers predate the hospital, and may come from an aisled hall, the earliest remains of domestic architecture in the city, which was then adapted to form the hospital chapel.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Three 17th-century town houses which were attached to the hospital were incorporated into model workers' flats in 1865, and converted to offices in 1978.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] St Nicholas's Almshouses were built in 1652 to provide care for the poor.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Several public houses were also built in this period, including the Llandoger Trow on King Street and the Hatchet Inn.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Manor houses include Goldney Hall, where the highly decorated Grotto dates from 1739.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Commercial buildings such as the Exchange and Old Post Office from the 1740s are also included in the list.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Residential buildings include the Georgian Portland Square and the complex of small cottages around a green at Blaise Hamlet, which was built around 1811 for retired employees of Quaker banker and philanthropist John Scandrett Harford, who owned Blaise Castle House.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The 18th-century Kings Weston House, in northern Bristol, was designed by John Vanbrugh and is the only Vanbrugh building in any UK city outside London.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Almshouses and pubs from the same period intermingle with modern development.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Several Georgian squares were designed for the middle class as prosperity increased during the 18th century.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] During World War II, the city centre was heavily bombed during the Bristol Blitz.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The central shopping area near Wine Street and Castle Street was particularly hard-hit, and the Dutch House and St Peter's Hospital were destroyed.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Nevertheless, in 1961 John Betjeman called Bristol "the most beautiful, interesting and distinguished city in England".
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] A dialect of English (West Country English), known as Bristolian, is spoken by longtime residents, who are known as Bristolians.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristol natives have a rhotic accent, in which the post-vocalic *r* in *car* and *card* is pronounced (unlike in Received Pronunciation).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The city is regarded as one of the last locations in England, along with Blackburn, to preserve the traditional English rhotic R sound.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The unique feature of this accent is the 'Bristol (or terminal) l', in which *l* is appended to words ending in *a* or *o*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Whether this is a broad *l* or a *w* is a subject of debate, with *area* pronounced 'areal' or 'areaw'.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The ending of *Bristol* is another example of the Bristol *l*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristolians pronounce *-a* and *-o* at the end of a word as *-aw* (*cinemaw*).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] To non-natives, the pronunciation suggests an *l* after the vowel.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Bristolian is characterised by use of *cassn't* instead of *can't* and *canst* and *dissn't* instead of *didst* and *didn't*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The second-person singular was retained and children were admonished with "Thee and thou, the Welshman's cow".
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] In Bristolian, as in French and German, the second-person singular was not used when speaking to a superior (except by the egalitarian Quakers).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] The pronoun *thee* is also used in the subject position ("What bist thee doing?"), and *I* or *he* in the object position ("Give he to I.").
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p01] Linguist Stanley Ellis, who found that many dialect words in the Filton area were linked to aerospace work, described Bristolian as "a cranky, crazy, crab-apple tree of language and with the sharpest, juiciest flavour that I've heard for a long time".
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol is represented by professional teams in all the major national sports.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol City and Bristol Rovers are the city's main football clubs.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol Bears (rugby union) and Gloucestershire County Cricket Club are also based in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The two Football League clubs are Bristol City and Bristol Rovers‍—‌the former being the only club from the city to play in the precursor to the Premier League.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol City, formed in 1894, were Division One runners-up in 1907 and lost the FA Cup final in 1909.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] In the First Division in 1976, they then sank to the bottom professional tier before reforming after a 1982 bankruptcy.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] They have been above Bristol Rovers in the Football League since 2000, and were promoted to the second tier of English football in 2007.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol City Women were formerly based at Twerton Park, but now share Ashton Gate Stadium as a home venue with the men's team.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol Rovers, the oldest professional football team in the city, were formed in 1883 and promoted back into the Football League in 2015.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] They were third-tier champions twice (Division Three South in 1952–53 and Division Three in 1989–90), Watney Cup Winners (1972) and runners-up for the Johnstone's Paint Trophy (2006–07), although they have never played in England's top division.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol Bears was formed in 1888 and has often competed at the highest level of rugby union.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The club played at the Memorial Ground, which it shared with Bristol Rovers from 1996, until moving to Ashton Gate Stadium in 2014.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] They changed their name from Bristol Rugby to Bristol Bears to coincide with their return to Premiership Rugby in the 2018–19 season.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The first-class cricket club Gloucestershire County Cricket Club has its headquarters and plays the majority of its home games at the Bristol County Ground, the only major international sports venue in the south-west of England.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol sponsors the annual Bristol Half Marathon and hosted the 2001 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has staged finishes and starts of the Tour of Britain cycle race, and facilities in the city were used as training camps for the 2012 London Olympics.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The Bristol International Balloon Fiesta, a major UK hot-air ballooning event, is held each summer at Ashton Court.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol is the birthplace of the 2025 Formula 1 World Champion Lando Norris.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol is home to the regional headquarters of BBC West and the BBC Natural History Unit based at Broadcasting House, which produces television, radio and online content with a natural history or wildlife theme.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The city has a long association with David Attenborough's authored documentaries, including *Life on Earth*, *The Blue Planet* and *Planet Earth*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The BBC announced in 2021 that it was moving the production of many of its programmes from Broadcasting House to Finzels Reach in the centre of Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has two daily newspapers, the *Western Daily Press* and the *Bristol Post* (both owned by Reach plc); and a Bristol edition of the free *Metro* newspaper (owned by DMGT).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] *The Bristol Cable* specialises in investigative journalism with a quarterly print edition and website.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Aardman Animations is a Bristol-based animation studio, known for the characters Wallace and Gromit and Morph.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Local radio stations, including BBC Radio Bristol, Heart West, Greatest Hits Radio Bristol & The South West, Hits Radio Bristol, Kiss, and BCfm, a community based station.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Television programmes produced in the city include *Points West*, Endemol productions such as *Deal or No Deal*, *The Crystal Maze*, *Tipping Point* and *ITV News West Country*.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Coming-of-age drama *Skins* and supernatural comedy-drama *Being Human* were also shot in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol was the former home of long-running BBC medical soap opera *Casualty* until 2011.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] In October 2018, Channel 4 announced that Bristol would be home to one of its 'Creative Hubs', as part of their move to produce more content outside of London.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Publishers in the city have included 18th-century Bristolian Joseph Cottle, who helped introduce Romanticism by publishing the works of William Wordsworth and Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Arrowsmith published the Victorian comedies *Three Men in a Boat* (by Jerome K.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Jerome) and *The Diary of a Nobody* by George and Weedon Grossmith.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The contemporary Redcliffe Press has published over 200 books covering all aspects of the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol is home to YouTube video developers and stylists The Yogscast, with founders Simon Lane and Lewis Brindley having moved their operations from Reading to Bristol in 2012.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has two major institutions of higher education: the University of Bristol, a redbrick chartered in 1909; and the University of the West of England, opened as Bristol Polytechnic in 1969, which became a university in 1992.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The University of Law also has a campus in the city.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has two further education institutions (City of Bristol College and South Gloucestershire and Stroud College) and two theological colleges: Trinity College, and Bristol Baptist College.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has 129 infant, junior and primary schools, 17 secondary schools, and three learning centres.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] After a section of north London, Bristol has England's second-highest number of private school places.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Independent schools in Bristol include Clifton College, Clifton High School, Badminton School, Bristol Grammar School, Queen Elizabeth's Hospital (the only all-boys school) and the Redmaids' School (founded in 1634 by John Whitson, which claims to be England's oldest girls' school).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Playing Out is a community interest company founded in 2009 in Bristol by Alice Ferguson and Amy Rose.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] It supports residents to organise temporary street closures creating play streets so that children can play safely outside.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] In 2005, Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown named Bristol one of six English 'science cities', and a £300 million science park was planned at Emersons Green.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Research is conducted at the two universities, the Bristol Royal Infirmary and Southmead Hospital, and science outreach is practised at We The Curious, the Bristol Zoo, the Bristol Festival of Nature and the CREATE Centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The city has produced a number of scientists, including 19th-century chemist Humphry Davy (who worked in Hotwells).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Physicist Paul Dirac (from Bishopston) received the 1933 Nobel Prize for his contributions to quantum mechanics.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Cecil Frank Powell was the Melvill Wills Professor of Physics at the University of Bristol when he received the 1950 Nobel Prize for, among other discoveries, his photographic method of studying nuclear processes.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Colin Pillinger was the planetary scientist behind the Beagle 2 project, and neuropsychologist Richard Gregory founded the Exploratory (a hands-on science centre which was the predecessor of At-Bristol/We The Curious).
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Initiatives such as the Flying Start Challenge encourage an interest in science and engineering in Bristol secondary-school pupils; links with aerospace companies impart technical information and advance student understanding of design.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The Bloodhound LSR project to break the land speed record is based at the Bloodhound Technology Centre on the city's harbourside.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol has two principal railway stations.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol Temple Meads, near the city centre, has Great Western Railway services which include high-speed trains to London Paddington and local, regional and CrossCountry trains.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol Parkway, north of the city in Gloucestershire, but within the conurbation, has high-speed Great Western Railway services to Swansea, Cardiff Central and London Paddington, and CrossCountry services reaching Birmingham, Manchester and Edinburgh.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] There are scheduled coach links to most major UK cities.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol's principal surviving suburban railway is the Severn Beach Line to Avonmouth and Severn Beach.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Although Portishead Railway's passenger service was a casualty of the Beeching cuts, freight service to the Royal Portbury Dock was restored from 2000 to 2002.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Following numerous delays, the two lines are due to be opened in 2026.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The M4 motorway connects the city on an east–west axis from London to West Wales, and the M5 is a north–southwest axis from Birmingham to Exeter.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The M49 motorway is a shortcut between the M5 in the south and the M4 Severn Crossing in the west, and the M32 is a spur from the M4 to the city centre.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The Portway connects the M5 to the city centre, and was the most expensive road in Britain when opened in 1926.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Private car use is high in the city, leading to traffic congestion costing an estimated £350 million per year.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol allows motorcycles to use most of the city's bus lanes and provides secure, free parking for them.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] In 2022, Bristol implemented a Clean Air Zone to reduce pollution by charging the most polluting vehicles to enter the city centre, with the money raised reinvested in transport.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Public transport in the city consists primarily of a First West of England bus network.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Other providers are Abus, Stagecoach West, and Stagecoach South West.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol's bus service has been criticised as unreliable and expensive, and in 2005 FirstGroup was fined for delays and safety violations.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Although the city council has included a light rail system in its local transport plan since 2000, it has been unsuccessful in funding the project.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Instead, Bristol has a network of five bus rapid transit routes, named MetroBus, which in part run on dedicated infrastructure.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The Metrobus project aimed to provide a faster and more reliable service than standard buses, improving transport infrastructure and reducing congestion, but has been criticised as a limited success because the routes are not fully segregated from other traffic.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The first routes opened in 2018, and as of 2025, they connect the city centre with Emersons Green, Bristol Parkway, Cribbs Causeway, Hengrove, and a park and ride near Long Ashton.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Three park and ride sites serve Bristol.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The city centre has water transport operated by Bristol Ferry Boats, Bristol Packet Boat Trips and Number Seven Boat Trips, providing leisure and commuter service in the harbour.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol was designated as England's first "cycling city" in 2008 and one of England's 12 "Cycling demonstration" areas.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] It is home to Sustrans, the sustainable transport charity.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The Bristol and Bath Railway Path links it to Bath, and was the first part of the National Cycle Network.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] The city also has urban cycle routes and links with National Cycle Network routes to the rest of the Country.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Cycling trips increased by 21% from 2001 to 2005.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] In 2023, Bristol Airport (BRS), located in neighbouring North Somerset, was ranked the eighth busiest airport in the United Kingdom.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] It handled 9.9 million passengers, an 14% increase compared with 2018.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-p02] Bristol was among the first cities to adopt town twinning after World War II.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital has its origins in the **Hospital for Sick Children** on St Michael's Hill founded in 1866.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The initial building was a large converted dwelling house on Royal Fort Road, south of the Royal Fort gatehouse, with accommodation for 40 patients.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the hospital's first salaried doctors was the pioneering female surgeon, Eliza Walker, appointed as House Surgeon in 1873.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] A much expanded hospital was built nearby to the designs of Robert Carwen in the Tudor gothic revival style in 1885.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Only the entrance building fronting on to St Michael's Hill now survives.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital was later renamed as the **Bristol Royal Hospital for Sick Children**.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The new Children's Hospital opened on 22 April 2001, replacing the old children's hospital on St Michael's Hill, at a cost £30 million.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the main aims of the design, in addition to providing the most up-to-date facilities possible, was to overcome many of the difficulties that face patients, families and staff.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In February 2014, it was agreed an inquiry would be held into the Bristol heart scandal, following heart surgery deaths at the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The inquiry published a report in June 2016, saying that “parents had been let down”.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] An extension was built to accommodate services moved from Frenchay Hospital in 2014, including neuroscience, scoliosis surgery, burns and plastic surgery, bringing all inpatient children's services in Bristol to one location.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2015, a neuro-rehabilitation unit was built to support the moved services.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In May 2014, a new helipad on the roof of the neighbouring Bristol Royal Infirmary became fully operational and will receive air ambulances from Bristol and the surrounding area, which will speed up transfer times for patients who are air lifted to the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The HELP Appeal supported the construction of the helipad with a grant of £500,000.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal is the only charity that fundraises exclusively for the hospital and the neonatal intensive care unit at St Michael's Hospital, to provide facilities and comforts for patients and their families.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal raised £12M towards the new building for the child-friendly hospital, which opened in April 2001.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Sculptures were decorated by a range of artists and celebrities, including Joanna Lumley, Sir Peter Blake, Cath Kidston and Jools Holland.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] At the end of the art trail, each sculpture was auctioned to raise funds for Bristol Children's Hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal has pledged to raise £3.5M for equipment for Bristol Children's Hospital, including a state of the art CT Scanner, an intraoperative MRI scanner, family facilities and child-friendly artwork to help save the lives of sick children at the hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] All funds raised by Gromit Unleashed will contribute towards this.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Bristol & Weston Hospitals Charity (BWHC) raises around £2M for all ten hospitals in the trust.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It provides equipment, ward refurbishments and additional extras.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It was formerly known as Above & Beyond and has existed since 1974.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2013, the charity's Golden Gift Appeal raised £6M.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 1997, arts consultant, Lesley Greene, was commissioned to develop an arts strategy for the new hospital.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] This project was committed to integrated designs, a commitment to consultation and the family.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Her active research programme led to the appointment of lead artist, Ray Smith, Eva Elsner, and Annie Lovejoy who contributed to the planning of the commissions programme.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Artworks were commissioned from more than twenty artists, many of which were site specific.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] These commissions were funded by the hospital's own fundraising arm, The Wallace and Gromit Grand Appeal.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Records of the Bristol Royal Hospital for Children are held at Bristol Archives (Ref.
[src:bristol-royal-hospital-for-children/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] 37424) (online catalogue) and School of Nursing records (Ref.
